    <!-- Abstract -->
    <div class="abstract">
        <h3>Abstract</h3>
        <div class="editable-container" data-section="abstract" contenteditable="false">
            <div class="edit-indicator">✎</div>
            <p>This paper introduces Authenticity Degradation Theory (ADT), a novel theoretical framework that challenges conventional understanding of human behaviour by proposing that initial kindness and care represent authentic human nature, whilst later difficulties reflect trauma responses rather than 'true colours' emerging. The theory integrates with the Witness Authority Framework, which transcends traditional victim-perpetrator binaries by establishing testimonial authority as a foundation for healing and justice. Through interdisciplinary synthesis of trauma psychology, attachment theory, neuroscience, and social psychology, ADT provides a comprehensive understanding of relational dynamics that honours both authentic expression and protective mechanisms developed in response to harm. The framework offers practical applications across clinical practice, legal systems, and social policy, with particular relevance for trauma-informed care and restorative justice approaches. This paradigmatic shift has implications for how we understand human nature, assess credibility in legal contexts, and approach healing from relational trauma.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="keywords">
            <strong>Keywords:</strong> authenticity, trauma responses, witness authority, relational healing, trauma-informed care, human nature, attachment theory, testimonial authority
        </div>
    </div>

